SIMPLE: monitor
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monitor
<hw>Mon"i*tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr.
<ets>monere</ets>. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf.
<er>Mentor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who admonishes; one who
warns of faults, informs of duty, or gives advice and instruction by way
of reproof or caution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You need not be a <qex>monitor</qex> to the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, a pupil selected to look to the
school in the absence of the instructor, to notice the absence or faults
of the scholars, or to instruct a division or class.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any large Old World lizard of the
genus <gen>Varanus</gen>; esp., the Egyptian species (<spn>Varanus
Niloticus</spn>), which is useful because it devours the eggs and young
of the crocodile. It is sometimes five or six feet long.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[So called from the name given by <person>Captain
Ericson</person>, its designer, to the first ship of the kind.]</ety>
<def>An ironclad war vessel, very low in the water, and having one or
more heavily-armored revolving turrets, carrying heavy guns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A tool holder, as for a lathe,
shaped like a low turret, and capable of being revolved on a vertical
pivot so as to bring successively the several tools in holds into proper
position for cutting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A monitor nozzle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monitor top</b></col>, <cd>the raised central portion, or
clearstory, of a car roof, having low windows along its
sides.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitorial</ent>⟦br⟧
